<body>
   
        <p>Let's introduce our leading example, which was actually our leading example in the
            E<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T173347-0500"?>xploratory
            <?oxy_insert_end?>D<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T173349-0500"?>ata
            <?oxy_insert_end?>A<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T173352-0500"?>nalysis<?oxy_insert_end?>
            unit as well.</p>
        <example>
            <p>In a study of the legibility and visibility of highway signs, a Pennsylvania research
                firm determined the maximum distance at which each of 30 drivers could read a newly
                designed sign. The 30 participants in the study ranged in age from 18 to 82 years
                old. The government agency that funded the research hoped to improve highway safety
                for older drivers and wanted to examine the relationship between age and
                <?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T173417-0500" content="the "?>sign
                legibility distance. (Data adopted with permission from Utts and Heckard,
                <?oxy_comment_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T173447-0500" comment="Is this a book? Please include year, and make book title italic"?>Mind
                on Statistics<?oxy_comment_end?>).</p>
            <p>Let's go through the entire process (outlined
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T173459-0500"?>o<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T173459-0500" content="i"?>n
                the previous page) for this example.</p>
            <p>
                <em>Starting point</em>: The researchers wanted to examine the relationship between
                age and sign legibility distance in the population of drivers. The researchers
                collected data from a random sample of 30 drivers:</p>
            <image style="block" src="../webcontent/image179.gif" alt="A two column table, with column
headers &quot;Age&quot; and &quot;Distance.&quot; Here is the data in the table, by row (in
&quot;Age: Distance&quot; format):
        18: 510;
        20: 590;
        22: 560;
        23: 510;
        23: 460;
        25: 490;
        27: 560;
        ...
        ...
        77: 360;
        79: 310;
        82: 360;"/>
            <p>
                <em>Exploratory Analysis:</em>
            </p>
            <p>The researchers display the data
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T173542-0500"?>on<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T173540-0500" content="with"?>
                a scatterplot:</p>
            <image style="block" src="../webcontent/image147.gif" alt="A scatterplot of Distance vs. Age.
Distance is on the vertical axis, and age is on the horizontal axis. The histogram has a negative relationship,
and it seems like it could be reasonably linear."/>
            <p>and observe a negative linear relationship in the data. In order to quantify the
                strength of that linear
                relationship<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T173602-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                the researchers supplement the scatterplot with a numerical
                measure<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T173615-0500"?>&#8212;<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T173613-0500" content=" -- "?>the
                <?oxy_comment_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T205045-0500" comment="make bold to indicate terminology"?>correlation
                coefficient
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T205048-0500"?>(<?oxy_insert_end?>r<?oxy_comment_end?><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T205049-0500"?>)<?oxy_insert_end?>,
                which turns out to be r = -.801, confirming the researchers' visual assessment of a
                negative, fairly strong linear relationship between age and legibility distance.</p>
        </example>
        <activity idref="_u5_m2_lbd11" purpose="learnbydoing"/>
            <p>
                <em>Inference:</em>
            </p>
            <p>The researchers would now like to see whether the observed linear relationship
                between age and legibility distance can be generalized to the entire population of
                drivers. In other words, the researchers want to check whether the observed
                linearity is due to true linearity in the population, or a pattern that could have
                happened just by chance.</p>
            <p>The test that the researchers are going to carry out is a t-test (most commonly known
                as the "t-test for the slope" for reasons that we are not going to get into) which
                is testing the following two hypotheses (step 1):</p>
            <p>
            <em><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T180739-0500"?>H<sub>o</sub><?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T180737-0500" content="Ho"?>:</em>
            There is no linear relationship between age and
            distance<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T180817-0500"?>.<?oxy_insert_end?></p>
            <p>
            <em><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T180744-0500"?>H<sub>a</sub><?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T180742-0500" content="Ha"?>:</em>
            There is a linear relationship between age and
            distance<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T180819-0500"?>.<?oxy_insert_end?></p>
            <p>and in general,</p>
            <p>
            <em><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T180803-0500"?>H<sub>o</sub><?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T180755-0500" content="Ho"?>:</em>
            There is no linear relationship between X and
            Y<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T180821-0500"?>.<?oxy_insert_end?></p>
            <p>
            <em><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T180808-0500"?>H<sub>a</sub><?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T180806-0500" content="Ha"?>:</em>
            There is a linear relationship between X and
            Y<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T180822-0500"?>.<?oxy_insert_end?></p>
        <!--<activity idref="_u5_m2_dig10" purpose="didigetthis"/>-->
        <wb:inline idref="u4_m4_qq2_tutor1" purpose="didigetthis"/>
        <wb:inline idref="u4_m4_qq2_tutor2" purpose="didigetthis"/>
        <section>
            <title>Comments</title>
            <body>
                <p>1. As we mentioned earlier, we are going to keep this discussion on the
                    qualitative side and in particular we will not go very deeply into <em>step 2
                    </em>of the hypothesis test. As for the<em> test-statistic</em> in this case,
                    we'll just say that the
                    test<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T181920-0500" content=", as mentioned,"?>
                    is a
                    t-test<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T181926-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                    which<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T181929-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                    as we
                    know<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T181932-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                    means that the null distribution of its test statistic (under which the p-values
                    are calculated) is some t<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T181939-0500"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T181939-0500" content="-"?>distribution.</p>
                <p>2. We are also going to focus
                    <?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T181959-0500" content="only "?>on
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T182003-0500"?><?oxy_comment_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T182036-0500" comment="is new wording correct? (There are other conditions that aren&apos;t mentioned here)?"?>only
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>some<?oxy_comment_end?> of the <em>conditions</em> that allow
                    us to safely use this t-test. They are:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>the observed data indeed look linear (otherwise it would not make sense to
                        try and generalize them)</li>
                    <li>the observations are independent</li>
                    <li>there are no extreme outliers in the data</li>
                    <li>the sample size is fairly large</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Note that in our example all these conditions are met; the data definitely look
                    linear, the observations (drivers) are independent of each other (since they
                    were randomly chosen), there are no extreme observations in the data, and a
                    sample size of n<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T182110-0500"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>=<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T182110-0500"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>30<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T182111-0500" content=","?>
                    is fairly large.</p>
                <p>For <em>step 3,</em> the researchers use statistical software to find a test
                    statistic value of -7.09, and a p-value that is so small that it is essentially
                    0. This means that it would be extremely unlikely (actually, quite impossible)
                    to get data like those observed if
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T182124-0500"?>a<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T182124-0500" content="A"?>ge
                    and
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T182127-0500"?>l<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101129T182127-0500" content="L"?>egibility
                    distance were not linearly related. In other words, it would be extremely
                    unlikely to get data like those observed just by chance.</p>
